✅ Why you need TLS:

When your remote Prometheus instances send metrics via remote_write to the central Prometheus, communication should ideally be encrypted using HTTPS (TLS), especially if traffic leaves the cluster or crosses networks.

To enable HTTPS, you need a TLS certificate (tls.crt) and a private key (tls.key).


---

✅ How it works clearly:

Central (receiver) Prometheus:

Uses the tls.crt (public certificate) and tls.key (private key) to enable secure HTTPS traffic via the OAuth proxy.

OpenShift's OAuth proxy will serve HTTPS connections securely with this certificate.


Remote (sender) Prometheus instances:

Need to trust the certificate provided by the central Prometheus.

Typically configured with:

insecure_skip_verify: true (quick testing only)

Or provide the CA (tls.crt or CA chain) that signed the central certificate.




---

✅ Recommended Secure Setup (Step-by-Step):

🔸 1. Generate a TLS Certificate:

Recommended: Use an internal Certificate Authority (CA) if available.

Quick self-signed for testing (use OpenSSL):


openssl req -x509 -newkey rsa:4096 -keyout tls.key -out tls.crt \
-days 365 -nodes \
-subj "/CN=prometheus-receiver.example.com"

Replace prometheus-receiver.example.com with your Prometheus route URL.



---

🔸 2. Create Secret in OpenShift:

Use these files (tls.crt, tls.key) to create a secret:

oc create secret tls prometheus-tls-secret \
  --cert=tls.crt \
  --key=tls.key \
  -n prometheus-receiver

The secret is mounted into OAuth-proxy container, as previously configured:

volumeMounts:
  - name: tls
    mountPath: /etc/tls/private
volumes:
  - name: tls
    secret:
      secretName: prometheus-tls-secret


---

🔸 3. Configure Remote Clusters to Trust Central Prometheus:

On the remote Prometheus sending metrics, you have two choices:

Option A: Use insecure_skip_verify (easiest, less secure):

remote_write:
  - url: "https://prometheus-receiver.example.com/api/v1/write"
    bearer_token: "<token>"
    tls_config:
      insecure_skip_verify: true

Option B (Recommended for production): Provide the tls.crt or CA to trust explicitly:

Copy tls.crt to remote Prometheus and configure it:

remote_write:
  - url: "https://prometheus-receiver.example.com/api/v1/write"
    bearer_token: "<token>"
    tls_config:
      ca_file: "/path/to/tls.crt"


---

✅ Simple Summary of Files:


---

✅ Recommended Secure Configuration:

Generate and securely store tls.key (private).

Distribute tls.crt (public) safely to remote clusters.

Avoid using insecure_skip_verify in production environments.



---

✅ Final recommended scenario clearly:

Receiver Prometheus: has TLS secret mounted via OAuth proxy

Remote Prometheus clusters: use bearer token authentication and explicitly trust central Prometheus's certificate (tls.crt)


Now you're all set for secure and trusted metric transfer!

